<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / UK Company News: SFO becomes involved as MTM reveals Pounds
20.6m pre-tax deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SERIOUS Fraud Office has become involved in the investigation into MTM,
the specialist chemicals company where the share price collapsed in March
leading to the resignation of Mr Richard Lines, founder chairman, and the
finance director.
A report by Binder Hamlyn, MTM's auditors, is to be forwarded to the SFO,
probably by next week.
Mr Ken Schofield, chief executive, who took over from Mr Lines 10 days ago,
said the SFO's position is that it wanted to look at the report following a
Stock Exchange insider trading investigation into the company.
The Binder Hamlyn report reveals transactions that were 'incorrectly
recorded' last year and in 1990 which boosted sales and possibly profits.
During 1991, Mr Lines sold 3.3m shares at over 200p, a price that analysts
believe would not have prevailed had the revised figures reported yesterday
been available at the time.
Yesterday's long-awaited 1991 results were worse than expected.
On an unaudited basis, pre-tax and pre-exceptional profits for 1991 were
Pounds 5.14m, down from Pounds 9.75m the previous year. This 1990 figure was
itself revised down from Pounds 13.5m to take account of the questionable
transactions.
Mr Schofield said these transactions involved MTM selling chemicals to a
bank at the year-end and recording them as sales. He would not say how much
similar transactions affected sales and profits last year but said there
were 'a whole raft of items.'
In addition, MTM has taken a Pounds 25.7m exceptional item. This included a
Pounds 17.5m provision to revalue assets to true market value.
As a result, pre-tax losses were Pounds 20.6m, down from an adjusted Pounds
7.9m on sales of Pounds 104m.
The company also incurred an interest charge of Pounds 7.39m on debt that
ended the year at Pounds 85m but which has subsequently grown to Pounds
109m. Debt rose partly to reverse Pounds 7.1m of sales which were taken last
year and should have fallen in 1992.
