<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week Michael Parkinson looked forward with keen anticipation to the
start of a new series of Rab C. Nesbitt and was surprised when I did not
share his enthusiasm. Had I never been stuck in a lift with a drunk Glasgow
football supporter, he asked. Yes, I said, I had, and while that was merely
unpleasant, this series was unpleasant and also packed with incomprehensible
dialogue. Somehow the attractions of drunkenness combined with stupidity and
aggression seem to have passed me by. But since Mr Parkinson is far from
alone (the yobbish Scot is now regarded as such a draw that the cover of the
current Radio Times is devoted to him) I will have another look (9.00 BBC2)
and try to plumb the hidden depths.
Earlier on the same channel viewers in the south-east get a regional
programme, First Sight (7.30) about British quarantine regulations being
relaxed under EC law and the prospect of '70 rabies free years' coming to an
end. The way some of the British talk you would think that people in
continental Europe were dying like flies from rabies. Actually the chances
of dying in an air crash are much higher.
</TEXT>
