<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour to abstain in vote on
Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs will be ordered to abstain in next week's vote on legislation to
ratify the controversial Maastricht agreement on European Community treaty
changes, the shadow cabinet agreed unanimously last night.
Their decision, in effect, brings to an end an impassioned debate in the
Parliamentary Labour party that yesterday showed itself divided on the
correct tactics to adopt in the light of a widely-anticipated Conservative
backbench rebellion.
At a heavily attended weekly meeting of the PLP, about eight MPs argued
vigorously that the party had several grounds on which it could justifiably
vote against the government. But Mr Gerald Kaufman, the shadow foreign
secretary, warned forcefully that to oppose the legislation would be
inconsistent with Labour's stance at the general election.
He was backed by Mr Neil Kinnock, the leader, who wound up the hour-long
debate by reminding MPs that an opposing vote could be used against the
party at the next election.
Mr Stan Orme, the PLP chairman, said that no MP present believed Labour
could defeat the government as it was recognised the Tory rebellion would be
limited and that the Liberal Democrats would almost certainly vote with the
Conservatives.
Liberal Democrat MPs agreed last night to support the Maastricht legislation
on its second reading.
But they will attempt to force debates during its passage on Economic and
Monetary Union, the European parliament and the social chapter.
The leadership's decision means Labour will table an amendment criticising
the government's European stance, but will abstain on the main motion. Some
Labour rebels can, however, be expected to defy the whips and vote against.
</TEXT>
