FT  14 MAY 92 / Legal aid checks criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CRIMINAL legal aid is being granted without proper checks on applicants'
eligibility, according to a report by the Commons public accounts committee.
The matter was investigated after the qualification by Sir John Bourn, then
comptroller and auditor-general, of the 1990-91 appropriation account of the
Lord Chancellor's Department. Sir John cited 'uncertainty as to the
propriety and regularity' of spending on criminal legal aid.
Magistrates' courts - which account for more than half of the Pounds 333m
spent yearly on criminal legal aid - attracted particular criticism. Sir
John pointed to problems with insufficient information on the grounds for
applications and lack of evidence about checks on income.
Applicants for legal aid are required to provide 13 weekly pay slips as
proof of income. The MPs found that pay slips were often not provided, and
sometimes not even requested.
'It is unsatisfactory that court staff should knowingly fail to ensure that
legal requirements are complied with,' the MPs said.
Expenditure on Criminal Legal Aid. HMSO, Pounds 9.75.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8266</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CENCNABZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920514
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Work on Edinburgh opera house starts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORK started yesterday on a Pounds 16.6m project to create an opera house in
Edinburgh. It is expected to be ready in time for the 1994 Edinburgh
International Festival.
The project involves the conversion of the large Empire Theatre, last used
as a bingo hall.
Mr George Younger, chairman of the Empire Theatre Trust - which is leading
the project - said sufficient finance from the public and private sectors
was in place. Bovis has been awarded a Pounds 12m contract as managing
contractor.
Mr Younger, who is also chairman of Royal Bank of Scotland, said the opera
house would cost about Pounds 20m, including the Pounds 3.5m which Edinburgh
District Council had paid for the Empire Theatre.
The public sector is contributing Pounds 15.6m through councils, Lothian and
Edinburgh Enterprise, the Scottish Tourist Board, Historic Scotland and the
Scottish Arts Council.
About Pounds 2.4m towards a Pounds 4m target has so far been raised from the
private sector, with contributions coming from banks and United Distillers.
</TEXT>
