<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Money Markets: Paper held back
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MONDAY'S lingering hopes about an imminent base rate cut were extinguished
yesterday, as traders in the sterling money markets hardened to the view
that 10 per cent base rates are here for some time to come.
In spite of yesterday's low rise in the April producer price index, the
market is convinced that the UK authorities are unlikely to respond by
bringing rates down now. 'For all the hype about low interest rates, the
market's perception is that we are hard up against Germany,' said one
trader.
A few market participants may be hopeful. The unwillingness of discount
houses in recent days to offer paper to the Bank of England has suggested
that market players think a cut could come soon. On Monday, there was a
shortfall of Pounds 270m in paper offered to meet the shortage, and that was
repeated again yesterday to the tune of around Pounds 100m.
'Historically, when interest rates come down, people do not offer paper
because they hope it might happen again,' said one trader yesterday. But
other market players read little into this, believing that it is due to
technical factors, such as a number of banks being long on money.
In the interbank market, period rates continued to form a virtually flat
curve: everything from 1-month to 5-month money registered a rate of 10 1/8
per cent yesterday. 6-month and 9-month money ended the day a fraction lower
at 10 1/16 per cent.
In the futures market, the June short sterling contract ended the day
trading at 89.93, a figure which assumes that base rates in June will be
10.07 per cent.
In the discount market, the Bank of England forecast a shortage in the
morning of Pounds 750m. In early operations, the Bank purchased bills
totalling Pounds 129m, of which Pounds 50m were Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8
per cent, Pounds 48m were Band-2 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and Pounds 31m
were for resale to the market on June 1 at an interest rate of 9 15/16 per
cent.
The forecast was then revised to a shortage of about Pounds 800m. In further
operations, the Bank bought Pounds 99m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per
cent and Pounds 117m for resale to the market on June 1 at an interest rate
of 9 15/16 per cent.
In the afternoon, the Bank purchased Pounds 327m of Band-1 bank bills at 9
7/8 per cent. The Bank provided late assistance of around Pounds 170m.
</TEXT>
