<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Midland chief eases Hong Kong fears over
offer - The Battle For Midland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A PRESENTATION yesterday by Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive of Midland
Bank, to Hong Kong's investment community has left a growing sense that the
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation's bid for Midland can succeed and
that it would benefit the banking group.
Fund managers had expected few revelations. But Mr Pearse provided
reassurance to HSBC shareholders in his commitment to the merger and his
view that the counter-bid by Lloyds Bank stood little chance of passing the
scrutiny of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
'If the exercise was designed to get Hongkong Bank shareholders to look at
this deal favourably, then I think they achieved this purpose', said one
research director who attended the meeting.
There had been considerable initial scepticism towards the deal from Hong
Kong investors. They were opposed to the dilution of high growth south-east
Asian earnings through the acquisition of a European bank. Suspicions remain
as to the benefits of global banking.
'The arrival of Pearse has helped develop an understanding of Midland by
Hong Kong investors. It also shows he is keen and it shows he gets on well
with the Hongkong Bank', said Mr Peter Philips, portfolio manager at
Fidelity International Investment Management. I can't think there will be
enough opposition to block it. Given the dispersion of shareholdings, if
there was any opposition we would have felt the groundswell by now.'
Fund managers said the meeting provided reassurance that Midland's earnings
cycle was in a strong recovery phase, while Lloyds Bank's interest in
Midland had already helped persuade analysts that HSBC could be on to a good
deal. The HSBC share price reacted favourably to the Pearse presentation,
climbing 25 cents to HKDollars 44.50.
The main concern in Hong Kong remains the possibility of the bank being
forced to sweeten its offer. This will clearly depend on the existence of
concrete alternative bidders.
But analysts took encouragement from the comments of Mr John Gray, HSBC's
deputy chairman, who also attended the meeting. He would not discuss the
possibility of a higher offer, but pointed out that such a move would be
likely to hurt the HSBC share price. This would lower the value of the offer
for Midland, which has now risen to 422p,, compared with 378p when the offer
was announced on April 14.
</TEXT>
