<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / News Corp advances 76% to ADollars 334m at nine months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS Corporation, Mr Rupert Murdoch's media group, yesterday underlined its
recovery from financial problems with a 76 per cent increase in net profits
to ADollars 334m (Pounds 142m) for the nine months to the end of March.
News Corp said the improvement in profits was largely due to better results
from its newspaper and television operations, offset by disappointing
results at Twentieth Century Fox.
The biggest contributor to profits was an ADollars 170m reduction in
interest expenses to ADollars 728m, reflecting lower interest rates and
falling debt after the group's USDollars 7.6bn (Pounds 4.2bn) debt
refinancing, completed in early 1991.
The reduction in interest expense was offset by an increase from ADollars
11m to ADollars 77m in the group's share of losses at BSkyB and Ansett
Transport Industries, the Australian aviation business jointly owned with
TNT. News Corp also confirmed that BSkyB, the British satellite television
operation in which the group has a 50 per cent interest, moved into profit
in March.
Revenue fell from ADollars 8.3bn to ADollars 7.7bn, mostly due to disposal
of assets and the flotation of a 55 per cent interest in the group's
Australian commercial printing business. Net profits were ADollars 437m,
after taking account of abnormal profits of ADollars 103m, mostly reflecting
the flotation of the Australian printing businesses. Abnormal losses of
ADollars 189m in the comparable period last year reflected financing costs
of debt rescheduling.
The result represents a recovery since the end of the year to June, when
News Corp made a net loss of ADollars 393m after abnormal losses of ADollars
714m. The group forecast 'significant' gains in profits in the current year.
At the trading level, US profits fell 17 per cent to ADollars 655m, on
turnover down 1.3 per cent to ADollars 4.8bn. News Corp said the lower
figures reflected the sale of nine consumer magazines in June, together with
foreign exchange gains in the earlier period. UK profits increased 158 per
cent to ADollars 275m, reflecting the transfer of satellite broadcasting
losses to BSkyB and a 49 per cent improvement in profits from the newspaper
division.
Profits from Australia and the Pacific basin increased 4 per cent to
ADollars 259m, helped by a 12 per cent improvement in profits at the South
China Morning Post in Hong Kong.
