FT  13 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory seeks probe into Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN, RALPH ATKINS and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TORY backbencher yesterday supported Labour calls for a full public
inquiry into alleged insider dealing, financial mismanagement and corruption
at the Lloyd's of London insurance market.
Mr Paul Marland, MP for Gloucestershire West, who is himself a Name, said
that the sooner such a step was taken the better. 'The fact is we are
investors and the market has been found seriously wanting,' he said.
Mr Marland is a member of a number of syndicates managed by Rose Thomson
Young and Gooda Walker, which are expected to produce some of the worst
results in the insurance market for 1988, 1989 and 1990.
His remarks came as other Conservative MPs responded furiously to
suggestions made by Mr Peter Hain, the Labour MP for Neath, that the crisis
at Lloyd's could result in the government losing its 21-strong Commons
majority.
Mr Hain said in an early day motion that this was because 23 Conservative
MPs could face individual bankruptcy and disqualification as a result of
their membership of catastrophe syndicates with losses totalling hundreds of
millions of pounds. If 'even half' of the 23 - including several ministers -
were indeed declared bankrupt, the government could lose its majority. It
subsequently emerged that one of those referred to in the motion was no
longer an MP.
Several of those pinpointed by Mr Hain yesterday denied that they faced
bankruptcy, while a number questioned either his motives or the accuracy of
his information.
Mr Archie Hamilton, a junior defence minister, dismissed any notion that he
might be made bankrupt. 'The sort of money that I am losing is not something
that would cause me serious financial embarrassment,' he said.
Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, said the prospect of having to
relinquish his seat for the reason suggested by Mr Hain was 'nil'.
Mr Henry Bellingham, MP for Norfolk North West, attacked Mr Hain for
publishing the motion, describing the action as 'a gross misuse of the
Commons order paper'. He added: 'I am in no danger of going bankrupt.'
Mr Winston Churchill, MP for Davyhulme, said: 'It is a very cheap party
political publicity stunt. I am not on any syndicate that could be described
as having catastrophic losses.'
Lloyd's criticised Mr Hain's motion on the grounds of 'faulty methodology'.
Lloyd's pointed out that Mr Hain did not take into account the fact that the
23 backbenchers he named are members of many other Lloyd's syndicates which
will make profits in 1989 and 1990 as well as loss-making catastrophe
reinsurance syndicates.
</TEXT>
