FT  13 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Extension likely on ITV takeover
ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID MELLOR, national heritage secretary, has agreed to consider further
a proposal to extend the moratorium on takeovers of ITV companies until the
end of 1995.
Central Independent Television has been campaigning against moves to relax
the rules on overseas stakes in Britain's independent television companies.
The rules could in theory allow companies elsewhere in the EC to buy all or
part of ITV after the end of next year. In most other EC countries there are
barriers to takeovers of television networks by foreign companies.
UK takeovers, which are subject to the approval of the Independent
Television Commission, are blocked until the end of next year. Mr Leslie
Hill, chairman of Central, wrote to Mr Mellor last month calling for a
two-year extension of the moratorium. Mr Hill argued that EC rules governing
television takeovers were unlikely to become fair before 1995.
Mr Mellor, whose responsibilities include the media, replied that he was not
yet convinced that an extension requiring primary legislation was justified.
The government is preparing a complaint to Brussels about barriers
preventing British companies from acquiring television organisations abroad.
