<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Paper industry seeks boost for
recycling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S paper industry risks destruction from imports unless its raw
material costs are reduced through increased recycling, the British Paper
and Board Industry Federation warned yesterday.
It said mill closures, job losses and increased imports of finished paper
were inevitable unless the government acted to increase the supply of paper
for recycling.
The federation called on the government to introduce levies to discourage
the disposal of recyclable paper in landfill sites. Similar measures in
Germany and France have increased the supply of paper for recycling and have
pushed raw material prices down.
Mr Dermot Smurfit, president of the federation, said raw material costs in
the UK, which account for 55 per cent of the cost of making paper, were
between 300 per cent and 400 per cent higher than in Germany. Mr Smurfit is
joint deputy chairman of Jefferson Smurfit, the paper and packaging group.
The federation said legislation on recycling would be popular in the UK. A
Mori poll showed that 89 per cent of the public supported legislation
forcing shops and offices to collect and sort waste paper and cardboard for
recycling.
The federation has launched a campaign to encourage commercial organisations
to re-cycle waste paper and cardboard. He added that only 30 per cent of
paper in the UK was recycled compared with 60 per cent in Germany - and the
UK proportion was falling.
Falling continental prices meant that companies in the UK could no longer be
expected to pay for their waste paper, Mr Smurfit said. The shortage of
recycled paper meant that companies were being forced to import from the
Netherlands and Germany, and the UK was the largest importer of finished
paper in the world.
</TEXT>
