FT  13 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Archbishop warns on scriptures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS should not quote selectively from Christian principles in support
of government policies if they wanted to have moral authority, Dr George
Carey, the archbishop of Canterbury, said yesterday.
In a rare speech in the House of Lords, Dr Carey added that it was against
Christian teaching to emphasise individual rights without referring also to
the individual's duty to society, and said that public morality could not be
privatised.
His speech comes soon after he aroused controversy with a sermon in which he
criticised businessmen who awarded themselves big pay rises during the
recession.
'All of us are commanded to love our neighbour and to subordinate ourselves
to the service of God and of other people,' he said yesterday.
'To emphasise individual rights without acknowledging individual and social
responsibilities to others is contrary to Christian teaching.'
