FT  13 MAY 92 / Notts Tec warns over pit closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTINUED pit closures in Nottinghamshire would have a 'devastating' effect
on the economic and social life of the county, the North Nottinghamshire
Training and Enterprise Council (Tec) warned the government yesterday.
It called for a national energy policy based on the use of coal as a
strategic fuel.
This is the first political intervention by a Tec, 82 of which have been set
up to bring training closer to the needs of the private sector and to foster
business growth.
'Everything we do on the training and enterprise front can be negated by a
rapid reduction of the (coal) industry,' said Mrs Pat Richards, chief
executive of North Nottinghamshire Tec.
The stand taken by the Tec reflects disquiet in the region's business,
voluntary and political circles about the plans of - and for - British Coal.
Nottinghamshire County Council has this week published its coalfield
strategy for this year. It opposes coal imports and urges support for
deep-mined coal.
The council and the Tec are to put pressure today on Mr Tim Eggar, energy
minister, when he visits pits in the county. They will seek assurances about
the future of the local mining industry under whatever organisation emerges
after privatisation of British Coal. The council and Tec are seeking a
meeting with Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to urge a
review of coal policy.
Letters, Page 21
