<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Braque and Picasso lift market: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE art market received a boost in New York on Monday night when Christie's
sold 91 works from the collection of the late Bill McCarty-Cooper for
Dollars 21.5m, (Pounds 12m), with an important late (1952) work by Georges
Braque, 'Atelier VIII', making Dollars 7.7m.
The other exceptional painting in the auction, 'Compotier et Guitare' by
Picasso, went to a private US buyer for Dollars 3.85m. Not only did these
two important paintings find buyers, but spirited bidding ensured that the
auction was 95 per cent sold by value. Mr Christopher Burge, president of
Christie's in the US, said the results were 'tremendous, sensational'.
Christie's was fortunate in offering a collection with an excellent
pedigree.
It had been put together by Douglas Cooper, a friend of Picasso and Braque
and one of the greatest collectors of 20th century art. In 1949 Cooper
adopted McCarty-Cooper, then aged 25, who inherited the collection on
Cooper's death in 1984.
Many of the paintings were acquired directly from the artist. In the case of
the Braque this included the provision that the work should never leave
France.
In addition to offering fresh paintings of undoubted quality, Christie's had
the advantage of dealing with a deceased estate. That helped to ensure that
reserves and estimates were kept low to encourage bidding. Three years ago,
at the height of the art boom, the Braque might have sold for nearer Dollars
12m and the Picasso Dollars 10m.
'Guitare sur une Table' by Juan Gris sold for Dollars 1.485m, slightly below
estimate, and another Picasso, 'Homme a la Sucette', for Dollars 968,000.
Both went to US collectors. A Giacometti sculpture in bronze, 'Buste de
Diego', almost doubled its estimate at Dollars 935,000.
This was the first successful auction for two years in the troubled
Impressionist and modern art sector. It will give confidence to the market,
but the very high quality of the works makes it untypical.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
