FT  13 MAY 92 / TUC moves to avert row over recruitment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the Trades Union Congress were yesterday trying to avert a fresh
row over inter-union recruitment which could jeopardise the admission of the
electrical section of the newly formed Amalgamated Engineering and
Electrical Union to the TUC.
Mr Norman Willis, general secretary of the TUC, yesterday wrote to all
unions involved saying that the AEEU had agreed not to go ahead with a
merger between its electrical section and Cabin Crew '89 while TUC-led
discussions were continuing.
Cabin Crew '89 is a 5,000-strong union of airline cabin-crew staff which
broke away from the TGWU general union.
The TUC hopes that the engineering section of the AEEU will veto any move by
the electrical section, formerly the EETPU, to take Cabin Crew '89, or any
other disaffected union splinter groups, into membership. Both sections of
the AEEU are voting on TUC membership next year.
Mr Paul Gallagher, general secretary of the electricians' section, responded
to a sharply worded statement from Mr Bill Morris, general saecretary of the
TGWU, by saying they would not allow other unions to run their affairs. Mr
Morris had warned the TUC that unless it took firm action to stop the merger
the TGWU would have to consider its own future in the TUC.
