<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Auditors face radical shake-up of their role:
Standard-setting body proposes enlarged report - Clear opinion on a
company's chances of survival to be included
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDITORS will be required to comment on whether a company can survive for at
least one year after its financial statements are approved, in a radical
shake-up of their role proposed yesterday by the profession's new
standard-setting body.
The Auditing Practices Board is proposing that from early next year all
annual company reports should contain a substantially enlarged audit report
giving an unambiguous opinion on the financial statements provided by a
company's directors.
Details of the initiatives are in the first three draft documents produced
by the board, which was created early last year. Mr Bill Morrison, board
chairman, said: 'This is equivalent to trains moving from narrow gauge to
wide gauge and coming out of a different station altogether.'
Two of the new statements provide detailed standards for part of the
statutory audit of all limited companies. They would fundamentally alter and
lengthen the text of the report provided in accounts.
The first addresses the issue of whether the company is a 'going concern' -
to determine whether it is able to survive for a period of at least one year
beyond the period to which the latest accounts refer.
Auditors would be required to assess more actively the directors' view of
their company as a going concern and use their judgment to identify
'material matters' such as inadequate borrowing facilities, litigation or
significant debts falling due.
They would also be required to look forward up to one year after the period
to which statements refer, well beyond the timescale demanded under existing
guidelines.
The second statement deals more generally with the format of the audit
report. It says the report should be addressed to the shareholders and state
the date on which the opinion is expressed.
It should describe and distinguish between the responsibilities of the
directors for the preparation of the financial statements and the
responsibilities of the auditors to express an opinion on these statements.
It would have to contain a clear and unequivocal opinion on the financial
statements.
The third statement lays out the roles of the Auditing Practices Board. It
has 18 voting members, including nine who are not practising accountants.
The document says the board will issue two forms of document in the future:
statements, which are mandatory, and practice notes, which represent best
practice on emerging issues.
The new standards establish six types of opinion with which the auditors'
report can conclude:
Unqualified opinion - no emphasis: the financial statements give a true and
fair view.
Unqualified opinion - with emphasis: the statements give a true and fair
view but are affected by 'fundamental uncertainties'.
Qualified opinion - partial disclaimer: all evidence reasonably expected to
be available to the auditors has not been obtained and evaluated.
Qualified opinion - disclaimer: the evidence has not been obtained and the
effect is sufficiently material to make the statements as a whole
misleading.
Qualified opinion - disagreement: the statements are not prepared in
accordance with accepted accounting principles or do not give a true and
fair view, but the effect of the disagreement does not make the statements
as a whole misleading.
Qualified opinion - adverse opinion: the effect of the disagreement is so
pervasive that the statements as a whole are misleading.
The documents are open for comment until August 31, and the board aims to
issue standards in the autumn applying to companies with year-ends after
December 31 this year.
Scope and Authority of APB Pronouncements, Pounds 4; Reports on Financial
Statements, Pounds 4.50; Going Concern, Pounds 4. Accountancy Books. PO Box
620, Milton Keynes MK9 2JX.
Letters, Page 21
</TEXT>
