FT  13 MAY 92 / Vauxhall to resist EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VAUXHALL, with second-biggest sales of new cars in the UK, has told dealers
it sees no reason to adjust prices in the wake of last week's critical
report from the European Commission.
The study of car prices found large differentials between countries for some
models at certain times between January 1988 and January last year.
According to the EC report five carmakers - Ford, Honda, Citroen, Mazda and
Audi - had at least one model with price differences greater than 40 per
cent in one of the five time periods selected.
Vauxhall, the UK subsidiary of General Motors of the US, said it had
'serious reservations' about the validity of some of the EC analysis.
Mr David Wallis, Vauxhall director of business planning, said it was 'hard
to accept the EC report, or to reconcile its detailed findings with the
alleged 'high-price' character of the UK car market'.
