<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Terminal plan will fly in face of local opposition: The need
for expansion at London's main airport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A fifth terminal at London's Heathrow Airport is an important but only
partial step towards giving the London region capacity to meet passenger
demand forecast to rise from just over 60m people this year to 170m by 2016.
Although BAA, formerly the British Airports Authority, yesterday tried to
focus attention on its plans to build the Pounds 800m-Pounds 900m terminal
at Heathrow, it conceded that it would have to consider building a second
terminal at Stansted Airport in Essex to cope with passenger growth in the
next century.
The Civil Aviation Authority also believes a new runway will be necessary in
the south-east soon after the turn of the century. A working party is
studying possible sites for the additional runway, which many in the
industry believe is likely to be built at Stansted.
But the fierce public debate and local opposition traditionally provoked by
airport expansion has forced BAA to adopt a softly-softly approach to its
long-term plans for its London airports.
Local authorities reacted strongly to BAA's announcement. They fear that the
new terminal would increase the number of flights at Heathrow, cause even
greater noise and disturbance and worsen traffic congestion on the
over-crowded M25 and M4 links to the airport.
However, for BAA and the air transport industry as a whole, an additional
terminal at Heathrow has become an urgent priority if the airport is to
maintain its position as a leading international aviation hub and
accommodate the steady growth in passenger numbers and a new generation of
large wide-body aircraft.
Mr Gunter Eser, director-general of the International Air Transport
Association, said: 'Terminal 5 is the key to the continued development of
air services to the UK. Without the terminal . . . Britain alone would stand
to lose a billion dollars of economic activity every year.'
Sir John Egan, BAA chief executive, warned that if the terminal was not
built, the UK air transport industry risked facing 'the general decline we
have seen in other industries'.
Other European airports such as Paris or Amsterdam would take over some of
Heathrow's share of the international passenger market, he added.
The tortuous process of planning applications (there are expected to be
several public inquiries) is expected to take five years. BAA hopes the
government will give the go-ahead for the project in 1997. That will enable
the first phase of the terminal to be completed by 2001.
The new terminal would provide additional annual capacity at Heathrow for
10m passengers from 2002, giving the airport total capacity of about 60m
passengers a year. The second phase would be completed by 2016, adding room
for an extra 20m passengers a year.
Even with the completion of the first phase of the project, demand is
expected to exceed capacity in the London area by 2005. With the completion
of the second phase, there would still be a capacity shortfall of 27m
passengers by the year 2016, according to current traffic forecasts.
That is likely to lead to construction of a second terminal at Stansted.
Although the Pounds 400m Stansted complex opened last year is still
struggling to attract traffic, BAA remains confident that the airport will
eventually fill up as passenger growth recovers from last year's downturn in
air travel caused by the Gulf war and the recession. Demand at Gatwick is
also expected to grow during the next few years.
Although a further runway will be necessary in the south-east, the expansion
of Heathrow will not involve construction of a fourth runway there.
'The new generation of larger, quieter aircraft will help to deliver many
more passengers without the need for any extra night flights or an
additional runway at Heathrow,' Sir John said.
Apart from accommodating the forecast 3.8 per cent annual growth in
passenger traffic between now and 2016, the project will also be closely
integrated with a broader scheme to improve road and rail access into
Heathrow.
In addition to the proposed fourth lane for the M25, BAA is discussing with
the Department of Transport plans to improve other road links to the airport
including the M4 and the A4. BAA is expected to be involved in the funding
of these crucial infrastructure projects.
BAA also intends to go ahead with its plans to open a Pounds 235m express
rail link between Heathrow and central London in 1996. But BAA's original
rail link project in partnership with British Rail has now been overtaken by
the government's privatisation plans for BR.
Sir John said he saw no big obstacle to halt the project, although it is
likely to lead to a different partnership to finance and eventually operate
the link. The new terminal would also be connected to the Piccadilly
Underground line.
Without improved road and rail links, the new terminal would do little to
ease the growing stress levels of air travellers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
