FT  13 MAY 92 / Banks press for Polish debt talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S commercial bank creditors want to start 'constructive negotiations
as soon as possible' on re-scheduling the country's Dollars 11.8bn (Pounds
6.6bn) bank debt. However, Mr Jeffrey Stockley, head of a working group of
the London Club of official creditors, said in Warsaw yesterday talks would
not resume until the government reached agreement with the IMF.
Poland is seeking a 50 per cent cut in commercial bank debt to match the 50
per cent cut in its Dollars 33bn official debt agreed last year with the
Paris Club of western governments.
Mr Andrzej Olechowski, acting finance minister, said final consultations
with the IMF would take place next month.
Officials from the IMF talks said an agreement with Poland could be
completed by the end of July, provided the IMF board accepted a Polish
letter of intent.
