<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Fall in core inflation to 3.8 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT revealed a lower than expected figure for core inflation
yesterday but this potentially good news for the economy was accompanied by
indications of continued weakness in consumer demand.
The Central Statistical Office said the index of prices of manufactured
products for domestic consumption rose in the year to April by 3.8 per cent.
The rise was the lowest recorded for more than four years.
But leading retailer Marks and Spencer - whose sales are tracked on a
monthly basis by the Treasury - said in its annual results statement that
consumer spending had yet to show an upturn.
Indications that the removal of political uncertainty after the April 9
election has so far failed to stimulate the economy were reflected in a fall
on the London stock market. It ended four successive days in which prices
had closed at new records. The FT-SE 100 index of leading shares finished at
2,722.4, down 15.4.
The inflation figure highlighted the lack of success of many manufacturers
to restore profit margins - which have suffered since the recession started
around mid-1990.
Meanwhile Sir Richard Greenbury, the chairman and chief executive of M and
S, said in announcing a 1.3 per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds
623.5m that the recession had not ended as far as his company was concerned.
Hopes of a sustained recovery later this year are linked to projections
about a broad increase in consumer spending, which accounts for two thirds
of gross domestic product.
However, Mr John Major, the prime minister, put a more positive gloss on the
economic outlook, emphasising the 'dramatic change' in business and consumer
confidence since the Conservatives' general election victory.
The inflation figure also contained good news for the government in that
ministers believe the strong pressures on manufacturers to cut their prices,
together with low wage settlements, will eventually spur increased output.
Between March and April, the index of output prices at the wholesale level
increased by 0.4 per cent, after a 0.7 per cent increase in March. That
pushed the year-on-year rise in the index to 3.8 per cent, after 4.5 per
cent in March.
The extent of the reduction in the year-on-year figure was partly explained
by this year's earlier than usual Budget statement on March 10.
The early statement meant the normal Budget-time increases in excise duties
for alcohol and tobacco showed up mainly in the March producer-price index
number, rather than in April.
The index of prices of products excluding food, drink and tobacco is the
Treasury's favoured index for core inflation. It rose in the year to April
by 2.8 per cent, as opposed to 2.9 per cent in March.
Further indications of weak inflationary pressures emerged from the index
for factory input prices. It showed a fall of 0.6 per cent last month
compared with April 1991.
Further figures for inflation - at the retail level - are to be released on
Friday. The year-on-year change in the retail prices index last month is
expected to be about 4.4 per cent, after 4 per cent in March.
Lex, Page 22
M and S profits up, Page 23
M and S results, Page 24
London stocks, Page 42
