<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Germany's engineering union gives employers ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OPEN hostilities between Europe's biggest trade union and the mighty German
engineering industry will break out on May 25 unless employers improve their
3.3 per cent pay offer.
The industry - which produces annual sales of DM1,000bn (Dollars 606bn) -
has been given until the end of this week.
Announcing his ultimatum and the starting date for the long-expected strike,
Mr Franz Steinkuhler, president of the IG Metall union, which represents 4m
engineering workers, said yesterday that his only options now were
'capitulation or strike'.
Gesamtmetall, the employers' association, said its 3.3 per cent offer
remained the basis for any further negotiation. A deal approaching last
year's 6.7 per cent would cost hundreds of thousands of jobs, added Mr
Hans-Joachim Gottschol, the association president.
Both sides have rejected arbitration. A structured deal giving more to the
lower paid, similar to that agreed in the recent 5.4 per cent public sector
settlement, is also ruled out.
The union claimed yesterday that such 'social elements' were unsuitable in a
workforce where pay ranged from DM2,000 to DM6,000 a month.
In the absence of a new offer, Mr Steinkuhler said, an extraordinary union
executive meeting would be called next Monday to decide which regional
members would be balloted for strike action. Voting would be from May 20 to
22. The dates ann-ounced yesterday comprise the final data needed to
complete the programming of a strike which seemed inevitable from the start
of negotiations in early March.
If it follows its tradition of seeking maximum effect with minimum outlay in
terms of strike pay, IG Metall is most likely to start by calling out
suppliers to the motor industry. The industry employs some 900,000 and has
annual sales of almost DM300bn.
Beyond the pre-strike rhetoric, there is wide agreement that German
manufacturing industry faces a drastic slimming cure as it strives to
restore competitiveness and cut unit labour costs. However, most plans are
based on natural wastage and early retirement.
Employers' threats of job losses have yet to make much impression on a
workforce determined not to see living standards undermined. Forced
redundancies are rare and difficult to implement in the rigid German labour
market, and unemployment benefits are about two-thirds of basic pay.
SPD attacks Kohl, Page 2
</TEXT>
