<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / International Company News: Olivetti loss worse than
expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLIVETTI, the troubled Italian computers and office equipment group,
yesterday announced a bigger than expected consolidated loss of L459.8bn
(Dollars 372m) for 1991 and passed its dividend for the year. In 1990 it
made a profit of L60.4bn.
Most of the loss came from restructuring costs as the company tackled what
it said was the 'most difficult year experienced by the information
technology industry worldwide'.
Olivetti is undertaking a wide-ranging restructuring programme to halt
declining growth in demand for computer products and confront the fierce
price competition.
Adjusting to the tougher conditions overshadowed its 1991 accounts. Almost
L290bn of last year's loss stemmed from redundancy payments and associated
interest and extraordinary charges.
A further L170bn was set aside to cover 'extensive process and industrial
restructurings' linked to last November's decision to scrap its former
complex divisional structure and adopt a simplified model. Although only put
into operation in January, the full provision for restructuring was carried
on the 1991 accounts.
The benefits of cost-savings on labour were partially held back by delays in
government approval for last year's job cuts, meaning that most of the
redundancies only took effect at year-end. Nevertheless, Olivetti's
workforce shrunk by 7,200 in 1991, more than double the rate of the previous
year, and helping to reduce operating costs by 2.8 per cent.
At operating level, Olivetti reported a loss of L28.3bn, while sales fell by
4.8 per cent to L8,607bn. The operating figure was slightly worse than the
company's earlier predictions of breaking even.
Olivetti did not forecast sales or profits this year. However, Mr Carlo De
Benedetti, chairman, has said that it hoped to break even in 1992.
Instead, the group stressed its financial solidity, and the signing of
important new ventures this year. Net indebtedness fell by L172.6bn to
L571.9bn last year, while net operating working capital dropped by 18.7 per
cent to L2,549bn at the end of last year.
On the sales side, first quarter revenues fell by 4.4 per cent against the
same period last year, or by 3 per cent when adjusted for disposals.
Olivetti reached agreement with Canon in March on a joint venture to produce
computer printers and it has just announced an accord to supply personal
computers to the McDonald's restaurant chain in the US.
Meanwhile, the rate of cost reductions accelerated as expected as part of
the group's continuing efforts to bring down its break-even point.
</TEXT>
