<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Donelon defies the sector trend with Pounds
3.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DONELON TYSON yesterday became one of the few construction groups able to
boast even a small increase in profits and dividend for last year. The
announcement lifted the shares 3p to 44p.
Pre-tax profits moved up from Pounds 3.03m to Pounds 3.06m, despite a 15 per
cent decline in turnover to Pounds 80.9m. A substantially reduced tax charge
led to an increase in earnings per share from 4.01p to 4.61p.
As a result the dividend is lifted 20 per cent to 1.2p (1p), when many
construction companies have been struggling simply to maintain payments.
Mr Sean Donelon, chairman, said the group had performed well in difficult
markets. He expected to maintain modest progress in the current year.
The group steered clear of speculative residential and commercial property
developments, and had not been required to make costly write downs on land
bought in the late 1980s.
One of its strengths is its tunnelling business which sells almost entirely
to British water companies
About a third of contracting turnover - down from Pounds 59m to Pounds 55m -
was generated from tunnelling.
Contracting profits, however, slipped to Pounds 4.5m (Pounds 5m) on lower
turnover from general construction. Contracting margins held up against the
current market trend.
Property development profits fell to Pounds 450,000 (Pounds 720,000) and
merchanting profits to Pounds 388,000 (Pounds 572,000).
On the other hand losses from the industrial insulation business, which is
being discontinued, were cut to Pounds 1m (Pounds 1.8m).
Net debt of Pounds 14m at the year-end represented gearing of 90 per cent on
shareholders funds of Pounds 15.5m. But borrowings were expected to be
reduced by more than Pounds 3m with negotiations at an advanced stage for
the sale of the Skelmersdale Estate industrial property development. This
would cut gearing to about two thirds of shareholders' funds.
</TEXT>
